%%%
# Hierarchical partial pooling — batting averages

The classic baseball example (after Efron & Morris 1975; Gelman et al.).
Each player $i$ has $n_i$ at-bats and $y_i$ hits, with an unknown true
batting rate $\theta_i$. The rates are *partially pooled*: they share a
common Beta population, so a player with few at-bats is shrunk toward the
league mean while a player with many at-bats stays close to his raw rate.

The Beta population is parameterized by its mean $\phi$ and concentration
$\kappa$ (rather than raw $\alpha, \beta$), which is what makes pooling
interpretable — $\phi$ is the league-wide rate, $\kappa$ controls how
tightly individual rates cluster around it:

$$\theta_i \sim \mathrm{Beta}\big(\phi\kappa,\ (1-\phi)\kappa\big),\qquad
y_i \sim \mathrm{Binomial}(n_i,\ \theta_i).$$

Placeholder data: $N = 8$ players with deliberately uneven at-bats, so the
shrinkage differs across players.
%%%

# --- Data (placeholders) ---
at_bats_data = [45, 45, 45, 60, 20, 100, 15, 250]
hits_data    = [12, 15, 10, 18,  8,  29,  6,  71]
N = 8

# --- Population hyperpriors ---
% League-wide mean batting rate, on the unit interval.
phi ~ Uniform(interval(0.0, 1.0))

%%%
Concentration of individual rates around $\phi$. A broad Gamma (mean
$\approx 40$): small $\kappa$ pools the players hard toward $\phi$, large
$\kappa$ lets each $\theta_i$ follow its own data.
%%%
kappa ~ Gamma(2.0, 0.05)

# Mean/concentration -> standard Beta shape parameters.
alpha = phi * kappa
beta  = (1.0 - phi) * kappa

# --- Per-player rates (partially pooled) ---
theta ~ iid(Beta(alpha, beta), N)

prior = lawof(record(phi = phi, kappa = kappa, theta = theta))

# --- Likelihood: hits out of at-bats, broadcast over players ---
y ~ Binomial.(at_bats_data, theta)

# --- Posterior assembly ---
forward_kernel = kernelof(record(y = y), phi = phi, kappa = kappa, theta = theta)
L              = likelihoodof(forward_kernel, record(y = hits_data))
posterior      = bayesupdate(L, prior)
